# TypeScript standards

## Imports: single quotes

Always use `'` in import paths.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD */
import { Panel } from "@components/Panel";

/* ✅ GOOD */
import { Panel } from '@components/Panel';
```

## String literals: single quotes

Use `'` for every string literal in code (props, variables, JSX text, template literals when no interpolation is needed).

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD */
const size = "normal";
aria-label={`Level ${level}`}  // attribute string uses "

/* ✅ GOOD */
const size = 'normal';
aria-label={`Level ${level}`}  // template OK when interpolating
```

## Class names: PascalCase

Class names always start with a capital letter.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD */
class navigationService {}

/* ✅ GOOD */
class NavigationService {}
```

## Class methods: normal syntax

Never assign methods as arrow-function properties. Use standard method syntax.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD */
class TowerState {
  tick = () => {
    this.advance();
  };
}

/* ✅ GOOD */
class TowerState {
  tick() {
    this.advance();
  }
}
```

## Functions: declarations, not expressions

Define named functions with `function` declarations. Do not assign them to `const`/`let` as function or arrow expressions.

This applies to module-level helpers, exports, and component functions. Inline callbacks (e.g. `onClick`, `.map`) may stay as short arrow functions.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD */
const formatLevel = (level: number) => `${level}`;
export const LevelBadge = ({ level }: Props) => <span>{level}</span>;

/* ✅ GOOD */
function formatLevel(level: number) {
  return `${level}`;
}

export function LevelBadge({ level }: Props) {
  return <span>{level}</span>;
}
```

## Function arguments: positional first

Prefer individual parameters over a single options/props object. Use one object parameter only when there are **five or more** arguments.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD — object wraps few arguments */
function placeRoom(options: { floor: number; slot: number; type: RoomType }) {
  const { floor, slot, type } = options;
}

function formatLabel(options: { text: string; bold: boolean }) {
  return options.text;
}

/* ✅ GOOD */
function placeRoom(floor: number, slot: number, type: RoomType) {
  // …
}

function formatLabel(text: string, bold: boolean) {
  return text;
}

/* ✅ GOOD — five or more, object is OK */
function configureTower(options: {
  height: number;
  width: number;
  floors: number;
  theme: string;
  unlocked: boolean;
}) {
  // …
}
```

**React components:** JSX always passes one props object at the call site. Destructuring `{ level, size }` in the component signature is fine. Apply this rule to helpers, services, hooks' internal logic, and any function you call directly — do not wrap those calls in a single object when fewer than five values are needed.

## No barrel exports or re-exports

Import from the module that **defines** the symbol. Do not add `index.ts` files whose only job is re-exporting from sibling files.

```typescript
/* ❌ BAD — barrel file (navigation/index.ts) */
export { useNavigation } from './useNavigation';
export { NavigationProvider } from './NavigationProvider';

/* ❌ BAD — re-export from another module */
export { definePage } from './definePage';
export type { PageId } from './types';

/* ✅ GOOD — import from the defining file */
import { useNavigation } from '@navigation/useNavigation';
import { definePage } from '@pages/definePage';
import type { PageId } from '@pages/types';
```

**Allowed:** a component's `index.tsx` as its own entry point (implementation lives there). A module may export symbols defined **in that same file** (e.g. a registry built from direct imports), but must not re-export symbols from elsewhere.
